{  
  "response_text": "The data reveals a systematic decline in destocking rates across households over time, with pronounced fluctuations in early years stabilizing into lower, persistent levels. In initial timesteps, nearly uniform destocking (6.0 average) indicates synchronized resource scarcity responses. Subsequent time steps show increasing heterogeneity in destocking behavior, reflecting individual agent adaptation to climatic variability (rainfall mean=200, std=100) through learning mechanisms. By later time steps, destocking persists at low levels (<1.0 for many households), suggesting systemic adaptation to resource pressures while maintaining pasture resilience. Notably, late-stage destocking patterns correlate with rainfall variability, with higher variabililty appearing to reinforce destocking thresholds. The absence of social learning (E-RO-SL1 inactive under homog-behav-types?) and disabled strategy switching (SL2-strategy-switch?=False) appears to limit knowledge diffusion, resulting in slower but steady resource management stabilization compared to potential heterogeneous population dynamics."  
}

